### Delegates in C#

A delegate is a type-safe function pointer. It holds a reference to a method and can call it indirectly.

### Declaring Delegates

```csharp
// Declare a delegate type
public delegate void Notify(string message);
public delegate int MathOperation(int x, int y);

// Methods matching the delegate signature
public static void ShowMessage(string msg) => Console.WriteLine(msg);
public static int Add(int a, int b) => a + b;
```

### Using Delegates

```csharp
// Create delegate instance and assign method
Notify notifier = ShowMessage;
notifier("Hello from delegate!");  // Invoke

MathOperation op = Add;
int result = op(5, 3);  // 8
```

### Multicast Delegates

Delegates can hold multiple method references:

```csharp
Notify notifier = ShowMessage;
notifier += LogToFile;
notifier += SendEmail;

notifier("System starting...");  // All three methods called in order

notifier -= LogToFile;  // Remove a method
```

### Built-in Delegate Types

```csharp
// Action - returns void
Action greet = () => Console.WriteLine("Hello");
Action<string> log = (msg) => Console.WriteLine(msg);
Action<int, int> printSum = (a, b) => Console.WriteLine(a + b);

// Func - returns value
Func<int> getNumber = () => 42;
Func<int, int> square = x => x * x;
Func<int, int, int> add = (a, b) => a + b;

// Predicate - returns bool
Predicate<int> isEven = x => x % 2 == 0;
```

### Delegates as Parameters

```csharp
public void ProcessData(int[] data, Func<int, bool> filter, Action<int> process)
{
    foreach (var item in data)
    {
        if (filter(item))
            process(item);
    }
}

// Usage
ProcessData(
    new[] { 1, 2, 3, 4, 5 },
    n => n % 2 == 0,       // Filter: even numbers
    n => Console.WriteLine(n)  // Process: print
);
```

### Anonymous Methods

```csharp
Func<int, int> square = delegate (int x) { return x * x; };
// Same as:
Func<int, int> square = x => x * x;
```

### Delegate Variance

```csharp
Func<object> getObj = () => "Hello";  // Return type covariance
Action<string> logObj = (object o) => Console.WriteLine(o);  // Parameter contravariance
```

> **Key Point:** Use `Func` for methods that return a value, `Action` for void methods, and `Predicate` for bool-returning methods. Delegates enable callback patterns, event handling, and LINQ-style method chaining. Multicast delegates call multiple methods from a single invocation.

### Real-World Example: Callbacks

```csharp
public void DownloadFile(string url, Action<double> onProgress, Action<string> onComplete)
{
    // Simulate download
    for (int i = 0; i <= 100; i += 10)
    {
        onProgress(i / 100.0);
        Thread.Sleep(200);
    }
    onComplete("Download finished");
}

// Usage
DownloadFile("file.zip",
    progress => Console.WriteLine($"{progress:P0} complete"),
    msg => Console.WriteLine(msg));

